          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What should OEM buyers verify about mAh specifications when sourcing power bank cells?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "When sourcing power bank cells, OEM buyers must verify: (1) that the mAh rating is measured at the cell's nominal 3.7V, the industry standard, and that the supplier provides actual tested capacity at 5V USB output (not just the cell rating), (2) the conversion efficiency percentage (premium GaN circuits achieve 85-92%, budget circuits 60-65%, this single spec determines whether a '10,000mAh' bank delivers 6,500mAh or 9,200mAh usable), and (3) cell grade certification, Grade-A cells from Samsung, LG, ATL, or CATL deliver 500+ charge cycles; Grade-B cells degrade to 80% capacity within 200 cycles. Always request batch test reports showing actual measured capacity at 5V/2A output, not just the cell manufacturer's datasheet specification."
          }
